s, the nuances, entanglements, and historic (dis-)continuities that have emerged from the middle ages to the present day in fictional configurations between the poles of love and economy.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 4aLiebe. 4aLiteraturanthropologie. 4aLiteraturwissenschaft. 4aÖkonomie.1 aBandhauer-Schöffmann, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoelderl, Artur R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEbermeier, Verena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEstermann, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeliszewski, Zbigniew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaminski, Johannes D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeckeis, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeckeis, Paul, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKemper, Angelika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrobb, Florian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKucher, Primus-Heinz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeyer, Ingo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoser, Gerda E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoser, Gerda E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNeymeyr, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoepstorff-Robiano, Philippe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRußegger, Arno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSauter, Corinna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g